# Draft Slack Message for CI Issue(s)

Use this rule when drafting a Slack message to inform people about one or many filed CI maintenance issues (e.g. for a pipelines channel).

## Required Scope

- Slack scope is limited to `#metal-infra-pipeline-status` (channel ID `C08SJ7MGESY`) only.
- Read Slack evidence only from local export file `build_ci/raw_data/slack_C08SJ7MGESY_last_30_days.json` (assume user already generated it with `tools/ci/export_slack_channel.py`).
- If issue is not CI-pipeline related, exit instead of drafting a pipeline heads-up message.
- Do **not** read the entire 30-day export file into context. It is large and must be queried in filtered slices only.
- Use targeted extraction (`jq`/`rg`) keyed by workflow/job/test path/run ID/error signature and `HIGH CONFIDENCE`, then inspect only matched snippets.

## Evidence Priority

1. Latest failing job logs on `main` for the issue's job (ground truth for failure details).
2. GitHub issue details and linked PRs.
3. `.github/CODEOWNERS` and recent commit history for ownership.
4. Exported Slack auto-triage data from `C08SJ7MGESY` as supporting evidence.

Auto-triage guidance must be treated as strong only if it explicitly contains `HIGH CONFIDENCE`. Lower-confidence triage is weak signal and should not drive owner selection by itself.

## Multi-Issue Aggregation

When multiple issues are provided, produce **one unified Slack message**, not one message per issue.

1. Build a normalized record per issue:
   - workflow
   - job name / job family
   - terminal failure signature (from latest failing job logs on `main`)
   - latest failing job URL
   - optional linked PR
2. Cluster issues that are "similar enough" to communicate together:
   - same workflow and same/similar job family, and
   - same terminal failure signature/error pattern.
3. Prefer a **single compact cluster** when possible:
   - If issues share the same terminal failure kind/signature, collapse them into one combined section.
   - In that combined section, provide one shared failure summary and one list of all issue URLs.
   - Only split into multiple clusters when failure kinds are materially different.
4. For each resulting cluster, include:
   - issue URL list (raw `https`)
   - one concise cluster failure description
   - 1-2 representative job URLs
   - owner pings scoped to that cluster only if they differ materially.
5. If clusters share the same likely owners, keep mentions consolidated to avoid noisy repetition.
6. If only one issue remains after filtering/grouping, fall back to single-issue structure.

**Infra-dominated failures:** When logs or the issue point at **runner or environment** problems—read-only filesystem / `EROFS` / errno 30 on shared mounts, missing or unwritable cache dirs (e.g. under `/mnt/…`), runner disk space, image or agent misconfiguration, pre-seeded artifact/cache absent on a read-only volume—**do not** default to **workflow or model `CODEOWNERS`** (the people who own the test suite or product area) as the primary pings. Prefer whoever **owns the runners, host images, and mounts** for that job’s SKU/label (issue body, infra contacts named there, recent `git log` on `.github/workflows/` or `infra/` when clearly related). Add workflow/product owners **only** if a **workflow or env change** (paths, env vars, timeouts) is clearly part of the fix alongside infra.

## URLs in the message (required)

- Use **full raw URLs** only (`https://github.com/tenstorrent/tt-metal/issues/…`, job-level Actions `https://github.com/tenstorrent/tt-metal/actions/runs/…/job/…`, PR URLs, Slack archive permalinks). Slack linkifies plain URLs in normal message text.
- **Do not** use Slack mrkdwn `<https://…|label>` (angle brackets and pipe)—many clients show that literally instead of a link.
- **Do not** rely on `#12345` alone as the only issue pointer; include the **https** issue URL at least once.
- When delivering the draft to the user, **do not** wrap the entire message in markdown **code fences** (triple backticks). Slack does not linkify URLs inside code blocks.

## Structure

1. **Heads-up line**
   One sentence: deterministic CI failure descriptor + raw **https** issue URL(s).
   - Single-issue example: `Heads up on this deterministic CI failure for a llama3.3-70b test — https://github.com/tenstorrent/tt-metal/issues/39837`
   - Multi-issue example: `Heads up on a batch of similar deterministic CI failures (same Blackhole health gate signature) across these issues: https://github.com/tenstorrent/tt-metal/issues/40742, https://github.com/tenstorrent/tt-metal/issues/40743`

2. **Context paragraph(s)**
   - Single issue: keep existing behavior (workflow/job + root-cause/area + latest failing job URL).
   - Multi issue (default): keep compact:
     - one combined issue URL list,
     - one shared failure-kind/root-cause line,
     - 1-2 representative latest failing **job** URL(s) as raw **https**.
   - Only use multiple grouped sections when failure kinds differ materially.

3. **Failure excerpt**
   Single issue: one line/short block from latest job logs.
   Multi issue: one shared excerpt when all issues match; otherwise one excerpt per materially different group.
   Prefix with `failure: ` if it's one line. Preserve the gist; trim long stack traces.

4. **PR + review ask (optional)**
   If PR(s) (draft or open) are linked and would close the issue(s):
   - Include the raw PR URL, e.g. `And here's an auto-generated PR trying to address it: https://github.com/tenstorrent/tt-metal/pull/12345`
   - "Appreciate an extra set of eyes"

5. **Mentions**
   - Single issue: suggest 2-4 people most relevant to the issue.
   - Multi issue: suggest one compact owner set that covers all included issues (typically 2-4 people total if one shared failure kind; 3-6 if multiple distinct groups). Add group-specific mentions only when ownership differs significantly.
   Use failure logs, issue body (workflow/job/path), labels, `.github/CODEOWNERS`, and recent commits to pick owners.
   Apply **Infra-dominated failures** (see Evidence Priority): for mount/ROFS/cache-on-runner failures, **prioritize infra/runner ownership** over the workflow’s product CODEOWNERS; say so in the context line if helpful (e.g. “looks infra-side: RO tt_cache on shared mount”).
   For each selected GitHub login, resolve profile name via `gh api users/<login>` and output mention as `@<human name>` (for example, `@salar hosseini`).
   Do not output GitHub handles (for example, `@skhorasganiTT`) and do not output Slack IDs.

6. **Auto-triage reference (optional)**
   If relevant auto-triage message(s)/reply(s) are found in the exported month of data **and** have `HIGH CONFIDENCE`, add:
   - `This auto-triage report may be of relevance:` followed by the raw Slack archive **https** permalink (no angle-bracket formatting)
   - In multi-issue mode, include one permalink per group when available; omit for groups without high-confidence matches.
   If nothing relevant with `HIGH CONFIDENCE` exists, **do not mention auto-triage at all** in the Slack message—no line, no footnote, and **never** say things like "no high-confidence triage found" or that you searched Slack. Pipelines readers only need the permalink when it exists.

7. **Disable warning (deadline)**
   End with a single sentence that the test/job scope may be disabled if unresolved. Use plain calendar language—**do not** say "end of business next weekday" or similar.
   - **Monday through Thursday:** use **the end of tomorrow** (e.g. "If this isn't fixed by the end of tomorrow, we'll plan to disable this test/job scope…").
   - **Friday, Saturday, or Sunday:** use **the end of Monday** (e.g. "If this isn't fixed by the end of Monday, …").
   Prefer **fixed**; **finished** is fine if it reads better. Keep the rest of the sentence short (get the pipeline green, note if a PR is already in flight).

## Tone

- Concise and factual. No fluff.
- Suitable for a pipelines/engineering channel; assume readers know CI and GitHub.

## Notes

- User will copy-paste into Slack and may edit. Output should be easy to copy as one block.
- Use double-newline spacing between logical lines/sections to preserve readability in Slack.
- If no relevant high-confidence triage is found in the 30-day export, still draft the message using issue/log/ownership evidence only; the copy-paste block must stay silent on auto-triage (no negative disclaimer).
- In multi-issue mode, avoid flooding the channel with one line per issue; summarize by group while still listing raw issue URLs.
- In multi-issue mode, default to "one error kind + one issue list" when possible; expand to multiple groups only for materially different failures.
